 in Ethnic Minority Entrepreneurship (based at DMU) will undertake a year-long placement with the Black Business Association (BBA, based in Birmingham West Midlands) to support an initiative to promote 'procurement readiness' among its members. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The placement will pursue four key activities: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>develop the ICT capabilities of the BBA's members;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>&amp;nbsp;intensive support of 10 'exemplar' African-Caribbean firms to facilitate &lt;br />e-procurement;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>enhance the capacity of the BBA to disseminate the importance of e-procurement to existing and new members; &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>support and develop the BBA's future strategy as a membership organisation.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The researchers will work closely with the BBA, practitioners and identified stakeholders to systematically support and deliver an action research methodology across five stages: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Assessment of ICT capabilities of BBA membership;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Identifying and developing exemplar firms; &lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Awareness events;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Strategy development and formal stakeholder engagement;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Solution development/provision.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The placement provides an imaginative exposition of the Government's policy objective of boosting enterprise in disadvantaged areas, and aims to do so by implementing and extending principles of good practice through action research. Finally, the placement is unique with regards knowledge transfer by providing placement for the academics within the BBA and for BBA staff to spend placement time at CREME. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-04-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-11-17</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>27488</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Finding for the research have been used to support support activities for diverse businesses in the attempt to increase eProcurement in the Leicestershire Region. Findings supported the Leicester Supplier Diversity research and engagement of EMBs/BMEs in tendering for Local Council procurement.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2008</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>CEDCEE3D-70B5-495B-97AB-EDF3DFD40183</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>546331390fce02.14733098</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The research endeavoured to examine and develop a framework for business support in the context of the environment at the time. The research identified exemplars (good practice for engagement in ICT development and business support) and benchmarked the Black Business Population and at the time stakeholders. Of the 10 exemplar businesses identified 3 businesses were supported and engaged in eProcurement tendering but not in the Birmingham region as planned but with Councils north of Birmingham. A further two businesses after the deadline of the research also have tendered and had success in wining small but important procurement opportunities.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The findings in the Birmingham research were applied in the East Midlands as part of a Leicestershire S2P Project led by DMU academics.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>E1752F5D-62DC-4880-88AE-C95F9128D535</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>546333ec656383.46002840</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://cremedmu.wordpress.com/2011/07/04/emerging-findings-from-the-s2p-project-barriers-faced-by-leicester-businesses-when-bidding-for-public-sector-contracts/</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">RES-186-27-0002</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-186-27-0002</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5E9AA4EC-49E3-4D6A-B545-79DA07CE39E0</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Management &amp; Business Studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>5E9AA4EC-49E3-4D6A-B545-79DA07CE39E0</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Management &amp; Business Studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>